item.description:
The AUD has seen a big pop higher since last week's RBA decision.

This was surprising, given that the comments made by the bank were very much in line with similar comments made in May.

Based on the small changes we've seen in rate pricing after the meeting, the strength in the AUD has been a bit of a head scratcher.

When compared to some of the usual correlated drivers like copper and the Yuan (as seen in the image below), the AUD's move higher seems a bit overdone.

That means a surprise miss in CPI data today might offer risk event traders slightly better bank for their buck (also considering that the AUD does have stretched long positioning among institutional investors).

For this week’s CPI release, some participants are expecting the MM measure of headline inflation to show a flat reading for prices, thanks to seasonal discounts on holiday expenses and clothing, plus a dip in retail gasoline prices.

However, the YY measure is expected to nudge up to 3.8% from 3.6%. That would be the highest YY reading since November 2023.
